=== Yashima Tomb's Front Stone Chamber === [[File:Yashima_misasagi_Yatsuishi.jpg|thumb|180px|Yatsuishi, or Eight Stones]] {{osm box|w|417313278|八つ石}} Near the roadway in front of the tomb, a late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} tumulus can be found, with its covering soil eroded to reveal large natural stones forming the ceiling of a horizontal stone chamber.<ref name="shishikoko195">奈良市史 考古編, p.195</ref> Measuring approximately 7 meters in length and 3 meters in width, the stones are known locally as "Yatsuishi" (Eight Stones). A local legend recounts that Prince Sawara, as he died in {{ill|Awaji Province|ja|淡路国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, cast nine stones, asking to be buried where they landed.<ref name="kadokawa1112">角川日本地名大辞典 29 奈良県, p.1112</ref><ref name="fudoki">奈良町風土記 続編, pp.68-69</ref><ref name="yatsuishi">Yamato Province 添上郡八嶋陵 八嶋明神八ッ石明神原因記</ref> Eight of these were found in this area, inspiring the tomb's construction and possibly the origin of the area's name.<ref name="kadokawa1112"/><ref name="fudoki"/><ref name="yatsuishi"/> However, archaeological evidence indicates the tomb predates Prince Sawara, being from the late Kofun period.<ref name="shishikoko196">奈良市史 考古編, p.196</ref> Attempts to remove the stones allegedly resulted in mysterious deaths or illnesses among workers, leading to rumors of a curse.<ref>八島町資料集</ref><ref name="kadokawa1112"/>
== History == Prince Sawara was accused of involvement in the assassination of {{ill|Fujiwara no Tanetsugu|ja|藤原種継|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and stripped of his title in {{ill|Enryaku 4|ja|延暦4th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (785). He died at age 35 while being exiled to {{ill|Awaji Province|ja|淡路国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where his body was initially interred.<ref>続日本紀</ref><ref name="shishikoko194">奈良市史 考古編, p.194</ref> Reports of his spirit causing calamities led to his posthumous elevation to Emperor Sudo in Enryaku 19 (800) and the designation of his tomb as a mausoleum.<ref name="ruiju">類聚国史</ref><ref name="kadokawa1113"/> Five years later, in Enryaku 24 (805), his remains were transferred to Yashima Tomb.<ref>日本後紀</ref><ref name="ruiju"/><ref name="kadokawa1113"/><ref name="chiisaki">小さき社の列島史, p.124</ref>
In {{ill|Kanei|ja|寛永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4 (1627), records in the ''{{ill|Sokokushi|ja|宗国史|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' mention the existence of '''Emperor Sudo Shrine''' and a temple near the tomb.<ref name="shishishaji545">奈良市史 社寺編, p.545</ref> These structures were later removed or relocated during the modernization of the tomb site in the Meiji period.<ref name="shishishaji545"/>
