== History == Prince Sawara was accused of involvement in the assassination of {{ill|Fujiwara no Tanetsugu|ja|藤原種継|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tanetsugu|qq=}} and stripped of his title in {{ill|Enryaku 4|ja|延暦4th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku 4|qq=}} (785). He died at age 35 while being exiled to {{ill|Awaji Province|ja|淡路国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Awaji Province|qq=}}, where his body was initially interred.<ref>続日本紀</ref><ref name="shishikoko194">奈良市史 考古編, p.194</ref> Reports of his spirit causing calamities led to his posthumous elevation to Emperor Sudo in Enryaku 19 (800) and the designation of his tomb as a mausoleum.<ref name="ruiju">類聚国史</ref><ref name="kadokawa1113"/> Five years later, in Enryaku 24 (805), his remains were transferred to Yashima Tomb.<ref>日本後紀</ref><ref name="ruiju"/><ref name="kadokawa1113"/><ref name="chiisaki">小さき社の列島史, p.124</ref>
In {{ill|Kanei|ja|寛永|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanei|qq=}} 4 (1627), records in the ''{{ill|Sokokushi|ja|宗国史|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sokokushi|qq=}}'' mention the existence of '''Emperor Sudo Shrine''' and a temple near the tomb.<ref name="shishishaji545">奈良市史 社寺編, p.545</ref> These structures were later removed or relocated during the modernization of the tomb site in the Meiji period.<ref name="shishishaji545"/>
